{"title_page": "Unorganized Borough, Alaska", "text_new": "{{refimprove|date = December 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2013}}\n{{Infobox U.S. County\n|county  = Unorganized Borough\n|state = Alaska\n| ex image           = NENANA DEPOT.jpg\n| ex image size      = 300px\n| ex image cap       = [[Nenana Depot]]\n|seal =\n|founded year = \n|founded date = \n|founded title = \n|seat = ''None''\n|largest city wl = Bethel\n|city type = community\n|area_total_sq_mi =323,440\n|area_land_sq_mi  =\n|area_water_sq_mi =\n|area percentage = \n|census yr = 2000\n|pop = 81,803\n|density_sq_mi =\n|web = \n|district = \n|time zone = Alaska\n|named for = \n}}\n\nThe '''Unorganized Borough''' is made up of the portions of the [[U.S. state]] of [[Alaska]] which are not contained in any of its 19 organized [[List_of_boroughs_and_census_areas_in_Alaska|boroughs]]. It encompasses nearly half of Alaska's land area, {{convert|323,440|sqmi|km2}}, an area larger than any other U.S. state, and larger than the land area of the [[List of U.S. states and territories by area|smallest 16 states]] combined. As of the [[2000 United States Census|2000 U.S. Census]], it had a population of 81,803, which was 13% of the population of the state.\n\n==Overview==\nUnique among the United States, Alaska is not entirely subdivided into organized [[county equivalents]]. To facilitate census-taking in the vast unorganized area, the [[United States Census Bureau]], in cooperation with the state, [[List_of_boroughs_and_census_areas_in_Alaska#Census_areas_in_the_Unorganized_Borough|divided the unorganized borough into 11 census areas]], beginning with the 1970 [[U.S. Census|Census]] and undergoing border or name adjustments most recently in 2007, 2008, 2013, 2015, and 2019<ref>https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/geography/technical-documentation/county-changes.2010.html</ref>:\n\n*[[Aleutians West Census Area, Alaska|Aleutians West Census Area]]\n*[[Bethel Census Area, Alaska|Bethel Census Area]]\n*[[Dillingham Census Area, Alaska|Dillingham Census Area]]\n*[[Hoonah\u2013Angoon Census Area, Alaska|Hoonah\u2013Angoon Census Area]]\n*[[Kusilvak Census Area, Alaska|Kusilvak Census Area]]\n*[[Nome Census Area, Alaska|Nome Census Area]]\n*[[Prince of Wales \u2013 Hyder Census Area, Alaska|Prince of Wales \u2013 Hyder Census Area]] (including portions of the former [[Petersburg Borough, Alaska|Petersburg Census Area]])\n*[[Southeast Fairbanks Census Area, Alaska|Southeast Fairbanks Census Area]]\n*former [[Valdez\u2013Cordova Census Area, Alaska|Valdez\u2013Cordova Census Area]]\n**Split to form Chugach Census Area and Copper River Census Area, effective January 02, 2019.\n*[[Yukon\u2013Koyukuk Census Area, Alaska|Yukon\u2013Koyukuk Census Area]]\n\nThis vast area has no local government other than that of [[school districts]] and [[Municipal corporation|municipalities]] within its limits. Many of the villages do have [[Tribal sovereignty in the United States#Tribal governments today|tribal governments]], however. Except within some incorporated cities, all government services in the Unorganized Borough, including law enforcement, are provided by the state or by a tribal government. School districts in the Unorganized Borough are operated either by cities, in those limited instances when the city has chosen to undertake those powers, or through the general guidance of the [[Alaska Department of Education|state Department of Education]] under the auspices of Rural Education Attendance Areas.\n\n==History==\nDuring the 1950s, when the push for the [[territory of Alaska]] to become a state was at its height, any municipal government was extremely limited and scattered. Territory-wide, there were no more than a few dozen [[Municipal corporation|incorporated cities]], and a small handful of service districts, broken into [[public utility district]]s and [[independent school district]]s. The service districts were authorized by the territorial legislature in 1935 to allow unincorporated areas limited powers to provide services and to raise taxes for them.\n\nThe [[United States Congress]] had forbidden the territory from establishing counties.<ref>{{cite web|title=Governing Alaska: The Territory of Alaska|url=http://www.akhistorycourse.org/articles/article.php?artID=135|work=Alaska History and Cultural Studies|accessdate=22 September 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927002516/http://www.akhistorycourse.org/articles/article.php?artID=135|archive-date=September 27, 2013|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The delegates of the [[Constitutional convention (political meeting)|convention]] which wrote the [[Alaska Constitution]] had, in fact, debated the merits of establishing [[County (United States)|counties]], and had rejected the idea in favor of creating a system of boroughs, both organized and unorganized.\n\nThe intent of the framers of the constitution was to provide for maximum local [[self-government]] with a minimum of [[local government]] units and tax-levying jurisdictions. The minutes of the constitutional convention indicate that counties were not used as a form of local government for various reasons. The failure of some local economies to generate enough revenue to support separate counties was an important issue, as was the desire to use a model that would reflect the unique character of Alaska, provide for maximum local input, and avoid a body of county [[case law]] already in existence.\n\nInstead, Alaska adopted boroughs as a form of regional government. This regionalization tried to avoid having a number of independent, limited-purpose governments with confusing boundaries and inefficient governmental operations. The territorial service districts had amounted to this much{{clarify|date=April 2017}}, but were seen by many as an important foundation for the government to provide services without becoming all-powerful and unnecessarily intrusive, an argument which surfaced time and again during various attempts by the legislature to create organized boroughs out of portions of the unorganized borough.\n\nAlaska adopted the borough structure by statute in 1961, and envisioned boroughs to serve as an \"all-purpose\" form of local government, to avoid the perceived{{by whom|date=June 2013}} problems of county government in the [[Continental United States|lower 48 states]] as well as [[Hawaii]]. According to Article X of the Alaska Constitution, areas of the state unable to support borough government were to be served by several unorganized boroughs, which were to be mechanisms for the state to regionalize services; however, separate unorganized boroughs were never created. The entire state was defined as one vast unorganized borough by the Borough Act of 1961, and over the ensuing years, Alaska's organized boroughs were carved out of it.\n\nAlaska's first organized borough, and the only one incorporated immediately after passage of the 1961 legislation, was the [[Bristol Bay Borough]]. The pressure from residents of other areas of the state to form boroughs led to the Mandatory Borough Act of 1963, which called for all election districts in the state over a certain minimum population to incorporate as boroughs by January 1, 1964.\n\nA resolution of the State of Alaska's Local Boundary Commission introduced in January 2009 spells this out in greater detail:\n\n*''WHEREAS, the 1963 Alaska State Legislature passed, and [[William Allen Egan|Governor Egan]] signed into law, the \"Mandatory Borough Act\" (Chapter 52, SLA 1963), dictating that certain regions of Alaska - those encompassing [[Ketchikan]], [[Juneau]], [[Sitka, Alaska|Sitka]], [[Kodiak Island]], [[Kenai Peninsula]], [[Anchorage]], the [[Matanuska-Susitna Valley|Matanuska-Susitna valleys]], and [[Fairbanks]] - form organized boroughs by January 1, 1964.<ref>[http://www.ci.valdez.ak.us/clerk/documents/Rep2021709.pdf The document on Valdez municipal website]</ref>\n\nFurthermore, 21 Rural Education Attendance Areas were established by the Legislature in 1975. This created regional divisions of the unorganized borough for the purpose of establishing rural [[school districts]]. Many REAAs were later absorbed into organized boroughs.\n\n==Regional Educational Attendance Areas==\nThere are 19 Regional Educational Attendance Areas in the unorganized borough.<ref>{{cite web|title=Alaska School Map|url=https://education.alaska.gov/pdf/schoolmap.pdf|work=Alaska education|accessdate=2019-08-09|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Regional name\n!Headquarters\n\n! REAA or Borough School Locations\n! Notes\n|-\n| Alaska Gateway\n| [[Tok, Alaska|Tok]]\n| [[Dot Lake, Alaska|Dot Lake]]\n: [[Eagle, Alaska|Eagle]]\n: [[Northway, Alaska|Northway]]\n\n: [[Tanacross, Alaska|Tanacross]] \n: [[Tetlin, Alaska|Tetlin]]\n|Northeast central Alaska area\n|-\n| Aleutian Region\n\n|\n| [[Adak, Alaska|Adak]]\n\n: [[Atka, Alaska|Atka]]\n\n|[[Nikolski, Alaska|Nikolski]] (closed)\n\n\n\n|-\n| Annette Island \n| [[Metlakatla, Alaska|Metlakatla]]\n\n|\n|\n|-\n| Bering Straits\n| [[Unalakleet, Alaska|Unalakleet]]\n\n|Norton Sound\n\n: [[Elim, Alaska|Elim]]\n\n: [[Golovin, Alaska|Golovin]]\n\n: [[Koyuk, Alaska|Koyuk]]\n\n: [[Saint Michael, Alaska|Saint Michael]]\n\n: [[Shaktoolik, Alaska|Shaktoolik]]\n\n: [[Stebbins, Alaska|Stebbins]]\n\n: [[White Mountain, Alaska|White Mountain]]\n\nSeward Peninsula\n\n: [[Brevig Mission, Alaska|Brevig Mission]]\n\n: [[Shishmaref, Alaska|Shishmaref]]\n\n: [[Teller, Alaska|Teller]]\n\n: [[Wales, Alaska|Wales]]\n\n[[Saint Lawrence Island, Alaska|Saint Lawrence Island]]\n\n: [[Gambell, Alaska|Gambell]]\n\n: [[Savoonga, Alaska|Savoonga]]\n\n|\n\n\n|-\n| Chatham\n| [[Angoon, Alaska|Angoon]]\n\n| [[Gustavus, Alaska|Gustavus]]\n\n|[[Elfin Cove, Alaska|Elfin Cove]] (closed), [[Cube Cove, Alaska|Cube Cove]] (closed)\n\n|-\n| Chugach\n|\n| [[Chenega Bay,  Alaska|Chenega Bay]]\n\n: [[Tatitlek,  Alaska|Tatitlek]]\n\n: [[Whittier,  Alaska|Whittier]]\n\n|\n|-\n| Copper River