 susceptible to organized borough incorporation, have been vociferously opposed to such incorporation, and say the status quo suits them just fine. Many point out that they would already live in an organized borough if they desired that lifestyle and the level of government which comes with it.\n\nOn the other hand, many Alaskans residing in organized boroughs feel that they unfairly subsidize residents of the Unorganized Borough, especially for education. In 2003, the Alaska Division of Community Advocacy identified eight areas within the Unorganized Borough meeting standards for incorporation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.commerce.state.ak.us/dca/lbc/boroughstudy/study_materials.htm|title=Legislative Direct for Unorganized Borough Review|publisher=Alaska Department of Commerce|access-date=December 1, 2005|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20051201233151/http://www.commerce.state.ak.us/dca/lbc/boroughstudy/study_materials.htm|archive-date=December 1, 2005|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Bills have been introduced in the [[Alaska Legislature]] to compel these areas to incorporate, though {{As of|2009|lc=on}}, none have been signed into law.\n\n==Major communities==\n{{Div col}}\n*[[Bethel, Alaska|Bethel]] (the largest city in the Unorganized Borough)\n*[[Cordova, Alaska|Cordova]]\n*[[Craig, Alaska|Craig]]\n*[[Delta Junction, Alaska|Delta Junction]]\n*[[Deltana, Alaska|Deltana]]\n*[[Dillingham, Alaska|Dillingham]]\n*[[Edna Bay, Alaska|Edna Bay]]\n*[[Fort Yukon, Alaska|Fort Yukon]]\n*[[Hooper Bay, Alaska|Hooper Bay]]\n*[[Metlakatla, Alaska|Metlakatla]]\n*[[Nenana, Alaska|Nenana]]\n*[[Nome, Alaska|Nome]]\n*[[Tok, Alaska|Tok]]\n*[[Unalaska, Alaska|Unalaska]]\n*[[Valdez, Alaska|Valdez]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Portal|Alaska}}\n\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat|Unorganized Borough, Alaska}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20051201233151/http://www.commerce.state.ak.us/dca/lbc/boroughstudy/study_materials.htm Legislative Directive for Unorganized Borough Review]\n*[https://www.commerce.alaska.gov/web/portals/4/pub/Model_Boro_RPT.pdf Map of proposed model borough boundaries] Alaska Department of Commerce, Community and Economic Development (1997)\n\n{{Alaska}}\n{{Unorganized Borough, Alaska}}\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:Unorganized Borough, Alaska| ]]\n[[Category:Alaska boroughs]]\n", "name_user": "Namangwari", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eOverview:note about changed names and borders of census areas", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unorganized_Borough,_Alaska"}
{"title_page": "Michael Strickland (blogger)", "text_new": "{{notability|bio|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n | name             = Michael Strickland\n | image            =\n | caption          = \n | birth_name = Michael Aaron Strickland\n | birth_date       = \n | birth_place      = \n | criminal_charge  = 2017: Unlawful use of weapon (10 counts), menacing (10 counts), second-degree disorderly misconduct (1 count).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oregonlive.com/portland/index.ssf/2017/02/guilty_man_who_pulled_gun_out.html |title=Guilty: Man who pulled gun out at 'Don't Shoot PDX' protest|date=2017-02-11}}</ref> \n}}\n\n'''Michael Strickland''' is a conservative blogger and for the ''Progressives Today'' blog and shares video on his [[YouTube]] channel called \"LaughingAtLiberals\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/user/LaughingAtLiberals/|title=LaughingAtLiberals|website=YouTube|language=en|access-date=2017-09-28}}</ref>\n\n==Whiteness History Month==\nAt [[Portland Community College]] (PCC)'s Whiteness History Month in April 2016, Strickland attended several events to produce film for his YouTube channel LaughingAtLiberals. A PCC spokeswoman said he was routinely \"pushing buttons\" and posting heavily edited videos about the events.<ref name=\"theen13\">{{cite news|url=http://www.oregonlive.com/education/index.ssf/2016/07/portland_colleges_ban_man_char.html|title=Portland colleges ban man charged with waving gun at Don't Shoot PDX march|last=Theen|first=Andrew|date=13 July 2016|work=[[OregonLive.com]]|accessdate=20 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Race and Sexual Orientation Based Harassment ==\nLaw enforcement say that Strickland has a past police report alleging \"possibly race-based threats\" against an attendee at a Portland vigil for the victims of last month's nightclub shooting in Orlando, Florida.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.oregonlive.com/portland/index.ssf/2016/07/man_accused_of_pulling_gun_on.html|title=Man accused of pulling gun on Portland protesters was armed with multiple magazines of ammo, prosecutor says|work=OregonLive.com|access-date=2017-09-28|language=en-US}}</ref> Strickland, who also participated in Portland State University's PSU for Trump group, was alleged to have participated in online harassment campaigns against lesbian and transgender students and also filmed and mocked students and activists along with PSU for Trump members.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://whoismichaelstrickland.com/|title=Michael Strickland {{!}} Michael Strickland of Portland is a white supremacist|website=whoismichaelstrickland.com|language=en-US|access-date=2017-09-28}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=LaughingAtLiberals|title=Raw, Uncut: Wackjob Students Takeover PSU Board Meeting|date=2016-06-05|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=He1lNosT6-E|accessdate=2017-09-28}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=LaughingAtLiberals|title=Triggliots Lose Their Minds At Trump Event|date=2016-06-10|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XiADgGSGHiM|accessdate=2017-09-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://thinkprogress.org/how-students-for-trump-terrorized-portland-state-university-88396c06c743/|title=How 'Students for Trump' terrorized Portland State University|access-date=2017-09-28|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==Don't Shoot Portland rally gun incident==\nAt a [[Black Lives Matter]] rally in Portland, Oregon, on 7 July 2016, Strickland pulled a [[Glock#9\u00d719mm Parabellum|Glock 26]] pistol and pointed it at protesters, including an undercover police officer. Portland police reported that Strickland's pistol was equipped with \"an extremely large magazine\" and had a round in the chamber.<ref name=\"koin13\">{{cite news|url=http://koin.com/2017/02/12/man-who-pulled-gun-on-crowd-guilty/|title=Man who pulled gun on crowd guilty|last=Weisberg|first=Brent|date=12 February 2017|work=[[KOIN]]|accessdate=13 February 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"pdxtribune07\">{{cite news|url=http://portlandtribune.com/pt/9-news/314304-193157-man-with-gun-arrested-at-downtown-rally-protesting-recent-police-shootings|title=Gun arrest mars peaceful Don't Shoot Portland rally|date=7 July 2016|work=[[Portland Tribune]]|accessdate=20 July 2016}}</ref> The police also reported Strickland was carrying five extra magazines for the pistol, all loaded.<ref name=\"pdxtribune07\" /><ref name=\"opb08\">{{cite news|url=http://www.opb.org/news/article/gun-pulled-black-lives-matter-portland-charges-michael-strickland/|title=Man Accused Of Pulling Gun At Portland Black Lives Matter Protest Appears In Court | last=Templeton|first=Amelia|date=8 July 2016|work=[[Oregon Public Broadcasting]]|accessdate=20 July 2016}}</ref> Strickland claims he was surrounded by several [[Anarchy|anarchist]] protesters who pushed and shoved him, and that he feared for his life.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.kptv.com/story/32398549/man-who-displayed-gun-at-downtown-portland-protest-arrested|title=Man who displayed gun at downtown Portland protest arrested|date=7 July 2016|work=[[KPTV]] Fox 12|accessdate=20 July 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"olive_07\" />\n\nPortland's police chief, Mike Marshman, said Strickland's actions at the rally were \"fully unacceptable\", stating, \"I'm very, very proud of the members of the Police Bureau who cautiously and safely enabled the protest to continue on. That's how it should be. To the men and women of the Police Bureau, please continue to do what you do.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.oregonlive.com/portland/index.ssf/2016/07/portland_mayor_police_chief_st.html | title=Portland mayor, police chief stand with faith leaders to deplore recent violence | last=Bernstein|first=Maxine|date=8 July 2016|work=[[OregonLive.com]]|accessdate=20 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nPortland police arrested Strickland at the scene, charging him with [[menacing]] and [[disorderly conduct]], both misdemeanors.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://katu.com/news/local/dozens-gather-for-blacklivesmatter-protest-in-portland|title=Dozens gather for #BlackLivesMatter protest in Portland|date=7 July 2016|work=[[KATU]]|accessdate=20 July 2016}}</ref> Law enforcement officials then processed Strickland through the Multnomah County Detention Center and released Strickland on his own recognizance.<ref name=\"olive_07\">{{cite news|url=http://www.oregonlive.com/portland/index.ssf/2016/07/dont_shoot_pdx_protesting_poli.html|title=Man pulls gun at Don't Shoot PDX protesting US police shootings|last=Ryan|first=Jim|date=7 July 2016|work=[[OregonLive.com]]|accessdate=20 July 2016}}</ref> The next day the state added two additional charges of unlawful use of a firearm, a class C felony.<ref name=\"fontana_08\">{{cite news|url=http://www.oregonlive.com/portland/index.ssf/2016/07/man_who_pulled_gun_at_dont_sho.html#incart_2box |title=Man accused of pulling gun at Don't Shoot PDX rally released from jail|last=Fontana|first=Francesca|date=19 July 2016|work=[[OregonLive.com]]|accessdate=20 July 2016}}</ref> At Strickland's arraignment, the judge set [[bail]] at $250,000, with Strickland being released after posting the required bail on July 18. A [[Multnomah County, Oregon|Multnomah County]] district attorney sought the high bail amount partly based on alleged race-based threats, including harassing texts and phone calls, reportedly made by Strickland at a previous [[2016 Orlando nightclub shooting]] vigil.<ref name=\"opb08\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.oregonlive.com/portland/index.ssf/2016/07/man_accused_of_pulling_gun_on.html|title=Man accused of pulling gun on Portland protesters was armed with multiple magazines of ammo, prosecutor says|last=Bernstein|first=Maxine|date=8 July 2016|work=[[OregonLive.com]]|accessdate=20 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn response to the incident and based on his activities on campuses, [[Portland State University]] banned Strickland from its campus for two years, and Portland Community College indefinitely banned Strickland from its campus.<ref name=\"theen13\" />\n\nOn February 10, 2017, Strickland was found guilty of all 21 counts: 10 counts of unlawful use of a weapon, 10 counts of menacing, and one count of disorderly conduct. He was sentenced to 40 days in jail, 240 hours of community service, banned from taking video of people or events for at least 2017, and is also banned from owning guns.<ref>http://www.kxl.com/no-prison-journalist-displays-gun-protest/</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=http://katu.com/news/local/man-who-pointed-pistol-at-protesters-banned-from-owning-guns | title=Man who pointed pistol at protesters banned from owning guns| date=2017-05-04}}</ref> During the hearing the court discussed finding in a pre-sentence investigation that Strickland had Autistic tendencies or Aspergers.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.kxl.com/no-prison-journalist-displays-gun-protest/|title=No Prison For Journalist Who Displays Gun During A Protest - KXL|date=2017-05-03|work=KXL|access-date=2017-09-28|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nOn April 1, 2020, Michael Strickland\u2019s conviction was affirmed by the Oregon Court of Appeal which rejected the arguments of Strickland noting that the facts of the case were undisputed.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://cdm17027.contentdm.oclc.org/digital/collection/p17027coll5/id/26442/rec/1|title=|date=2020-04-01|work=Oregon Court of Appeals|access-date=2020-04-02|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{YouTube|FH7aTp8DsVI|Man pulls gun on crowd of Portland protesters}}\n* {{YouTube|GjjhwQKcxVc|Footage Shows Counter-Protester Pulling Gun on Portland\u2019s Black Lives Matter March}} published by ''[[Willamette Week]]''\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Strickland, Michael}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American bloggers]]\n[[Category:American criminals]]\n[[Category:American political writers]]\n[[Category:Politics of Oregon]]\n[[Category:Writers from Portland, Oregon]]\n[[Category:Year of birth uncertain]]\n[[Category:21st-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{notability|bi